{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528270","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528270"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:40:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:40:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14281"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14281"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.04,0.15,0.04,0.71]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6976"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54583"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6976"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14281"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40099"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1475"},{"type":"tags","id":"1803"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16394"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40269"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54583"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of itchy, red eyelids and a gritty sensation in both eyes. She has gastroeosophageal reflux and takes omeprazole regularly. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Ophthalmic examination reveals erythematous and slightly swollen eyelid margins with crusting around the base of the eyelashes. There are no signs of corneal involvement or visual acuity changes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical corticosteroid drops","Topical cyclosporine","Artificial tears","Oral doxycycline","Warm compresses and lid hygiene"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic symptoms and signs of blepharitis, which is an inflammatory condition of the eyelid margins. The most appropriate first-line treatment for blepharitis is \u003Cstrong\u003Ewarm compresses and lid hygiene\u003C/strong\u003E. This conservative approach helps to loosen and remove the crusts and debris that accumulate on the eyelid margins, unblock the meibomian glands, and reduce bacterial load.  Anterior blepharitis is associated with inflammation of the anterior eyelid margin and dermatitis,  and posterior blepharitis is associated with meibomian gland dysfunction and rosacea though there are often overlaps.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral doxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E is sometimes used in the management of blepharitis, particularly in cases associated with rosacea or those refractory to first-line treatments. However, it is not the first-line treatment and would be considered only if conservative measures fail.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical corticosteroid drops\u003C/strong\u003E may be used in short courses for severe inflammatory blepharitis, but they are not recommended as first-line treatment due to potential side effects with long-term use, including increased intraocular pressure and cataract formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical cyclosporine\u003C/strong\u003E is sometimes used in cases of blepharitis associated with dry eye syndrome, but it is not a first-line treatment for uncomplicated blepharitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArtificial tears\u003C/strong\u003E can provide symptomatic relief in blepharitis, especially when associated with dry eye symptoms. However, they do not address the underlying cause and are not considered the primary treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of blepharitis typically involves a stepwise approach. After warm compresses and lid hygiene, if symptoms persist, topical antibiotics might be considered. For refractory cases, oral antibiotics (such as doxycycline or azithromycin) or other treatments may be necessary. Patient education about the chronic nature of blepharitis and the importance of long-term lid hygiene is crucial for successful management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Warm compresses and lid hygiene are the first-line treatment for blepharitis.","Topical antibiotics are used for moderate to severe cases of blepharitis or when there are signs of infection."],"references":["Wong K. Blepharitis. Dermnet NZ. 2009. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/blepharitis","Onghanseng N, Ng SM, Halim MS, Nguyen QD. Oral antibiotics for chronic blepharitis. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2021 Jun 9;6(6):CD013697. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8189606/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40099"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14281"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40099","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40099"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-08T06:59:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-08T07:00:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6976"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54583"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"created